In .NET MAUI, you configure platform lifecycle events via the `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` builder method in `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;

public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
    {
#if ANDROID
        events.AddAndroid(android => android
            .OnPause(activity =>
            {
                // Runs when the activity is pausing
            })
            .OnStop(activity =>
            {
                // Runs when the activity is no longer visible
            }));
#endif

#if IOS
        events.AddiOS(ios => ios
            .DidEnterBackground(application =>
            {
                // Runs when the app enters the background
            }));
#endif
    });

    return builder.Build();
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`ConfigureLifecycleEvents`** is the single entry point for all platform lifecycle hooks.
- Use **`#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS`** preprocessor directives (or platform-specific folders) to keep platform code separated.
- **Android** exposes `OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnResume`, `OnDestroy`, etc. (mirrors the `Activity` lifecycle).
- **iOS** exposes `DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate`, etc. (mirrors `UIApplicationDelegate`).
- The delegate parameters (`activity`, `application`) give you the native platform object if you need it.
